Model Identification¶

Run Sequence Plot¶

In [16]:
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.plot(data, linestyle='-')
plt.title('Run Sequence Plot (23MDS003)')
plt.xlabel('Observation')
plt.ylabel('Particle Size')
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

We can make the following conclusions from the run sequence plot:

  • The data show strong and positive autocorrelation.
  • There does not seem to be a significant trend or any obvious seasonal pattern in the data.

Autocorrelation Plot¶

In [18]:
from statsmodels.graphics.tsaplots import plot_acf
In [20]:
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plot_acf(data, lags=50)
plt.title('Autocorrelation Plot of Particle Size (23MDS003)')
plt.xlabel('Lag')
plt.ylabel('Autocorrelation')
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

<Figure size 1000x600 with 0 Axes>

autocorrelation plot shows that the sample autocorrelations are very strong and positive and decay very slowly.

Run sequence plot of the differenced data¶

import numpy as np

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))

plt.xlabel('Observation')
plt.ylabel('Differenced Particle Size')
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

Run sequence plot of the differenced data shows that the mean of the differenced data is around zero, with the differenced data less autocorrelated than the original data.

Based on above graph we try ARIMA(2,1,0) and ARIMA(0,1,1)¶

ARIMA¶

In [38]:
# Fit ARIMA(2,1,0) model
arima_210 = ARIMA(differenced_data, order=(2,1,0))
arima_210_results = arima_210.fit()

# Fit ARIMA(0,1,1) model
arima_011 = ARIMA(differenced_data, order=(0,1,1))
arima_011_results = arima_011.fit()

# Compare AIC values
print("ARIMA(2,1,0) AIC:", arima_210_results.aic)
print("ARIMA(0,1,1) AIC:", arima_011_results.aic)

ARIMA(2,1,0) AIC: 906.00557011776
ARIMA(0,1,1) AIC: 770.4358473140555

Model Validation¶

In [74]:
import seaborn as sns
fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(12, 10))
fig.suptitle('4-Plot of Residuals from ARIMA(2,1,0) Model of 23MDS003')

axs[0, 0].plot(residuals)
axs[0, 0].set_title('Run Sequence Plot')
axs[0, 0].set_xlabel('Time')
axs[0, 0].set_ylabel('Residuals')

pd.plotting.lag_plot(residuals, lag=1, ax=axs[0, 1])
axs[0, 1].set_title('Lag Plot')
axs[0, 1].set_xlabel('Residuals (t)')
axs[0, 1].set_ylabel('Residuals (t-1)')

sns.histplot(residuals, kde=True, ax=axs[1, 0])
axs[1, 0].set_title('Histogram')
axs[1, 0].set_xlabel('Residuals')

stats.probplot(residuals, dist="norm", plot=axs[1, 1])
axs[1, 1].set_title('Normal Probability Plot')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Autocorrelation plot shows that for the first 25 lags, all sample autocorrelations except those at lags 7 and 18 fall inside the 95 % confidence bounds indicating the residuals appear to be random.¶

In [83]:

plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

<Figure size 1000x600 with 0 Axes>

Autocorrelation plot shows that for the first 25 lags, all sample autocorrelations except those at lags 7 and 18 fall inside the 95 % confidence bounds indicating the residuals appear to be random.

axs[0, 0].plot(residuals)
axs[0, 0].set_title('Run Sequence Plot')

axs[0, 0].set_ylabel('Residuals')

axs[0, 1].set_title('Lag Plot')
axs[0, 1].set_xlabel('Residuals (t)')
axs[0, 1].set_ylabel('Residuals (t-1)')

axs[1, 0].set_title('Histogram')

axs[1, 1].set_title('Normal Probability Plot')

plt.show()
